"# Chapter 15 — HTTP server

Composer v1.1 shipped an HTTP host. Kids run a small server on their local machine and share a link so a friend on the same wifi can play their cart in a browser. The server hosts carts from a local directory and gates the composer view behind a local-only permission by default.

## 15.1 The four verbs

```
(http/serve :port N :cart-dir DIR :compose-perm 'local-only)  ;; -> server-record
(http/wait-until-ready server [timeout-ms])                    ;; -> server-record with bound port
(http/stop server)                                             ;; -> #t
(http/serve-info server)                                       ;; -> alist of server info
```

All four verify against the runtime.

## 15.2 Starting the server

```scheme
(define s (http/serve :port 8080 :cart-dir \"carts\" :compose-perm 'local-only))
```

Starts an HTTP server on port 8080 serving carts from the `carts/` directory. `:compose-perm 'local-only` gates the `/compose/` route to local requests.

If `:port 0` is passed, the server picks an unused port; use `http/wait-until-ready` to learn the actual port.

## 15.3 Waiting for the server to bind

```scheme
(http/wait-until-ready s 2000)
```

Waits up to 2000 milliseconds for the server to bind. Returns the server record with the actual `:port` field populated.

## 15.4 Stopping the server

```scheme
(http/stop s)
;; => #t
```

Closes the server and removes it from the registry.

## 15.5 Server info

```scheme
(http/serve-info s)
;; => ((:id 1) (:port 8080) (:cart-dir \"/absolute/path/carts\") (:compose-perm local-only))
```

Returns an alist describing the server.

## 15.6 The three routes

The server exposes three route families:

1. `/` — landing page listing carts.
2. `/play/:cart` — browser shell for playing a cart. Public.
3. `/compose/:cart` — browser shell for composing a cart. Permission-gated.

## 15.7 The landing page

Visit `http://localhost:8080/` and you see:

- The ASCII tree logo.
- Three brand stripes (pink, green, brown).
- A list of all carts in the cart directory, each with a play link and a compose link.

The landing page is HTML with inline CSS. Nothing served from a CDN. Everything the browser needs comes from the server itself.

## 15.8 The play route

`/play/:cart` serves a page that shows the cart's source (for v1.1) and a link to compose. The browser runtime that actually executes the cart lives in a later wave — v1.1 gets you as far as viewing and sharing the source. The security review in the source documents this: the play route is READ-ONLY delivery of the composer bundle.

## 15.9 The compose route

`/compose/:cart` opens a compose view. By default `:compose-perm 'local-only` means only requests from 127.0.0.1 or ::1 can hit this route. A remote request receives a 403.

The permission check reads the raw socket's remote address. X-Forwarded-For and other client-supplied headers are IGNORED. A remote client cannot lie its way past the local-only gate by setting a header.

## 15.10 Path-traversal defense

The server refuses:

- URLs containing null bytes.
- URLs containing `..` (literal, not URL-encoded).
- Cart names not matching `/^[A-Za-z0-9._-]+$/` per segment.
- Cart names with more than 4 path segments.
- Cart names longer than 256 characters.

Every cart name is decoded, split on `/`, checked segment-by-segment, and only served if the resolved path is still under the cart directory. A cart named `../../etc/passwd` will not resolve; the server returns 404.

The full path-safety code is in `lib/net/http-serve.js` — `safeCartPath`, `safeCartPathWithSubdir`, and `safeResolveCartDir`. These are the functions Appendix H covers in depth.

## 15.11 GET only

Only GET requests are honored. POST, PUT, DELETE return 405. This is deliberate: v1.1 does not accept cart writes over HTTP. Edits round-trip through the composer's own save/load, not the HTTP layer. A later wave may add a WebSocket edit channel — until then, the HTTP surface is read-only.

## 15.12 Compose-vs-play separation

The `compose-perm` option is the whole model:

- `'local-only` (default) — the compose view only opens for requests from the machine running the server. A remote friend can play carts but cannot compose them.
- `'anyone` — opens compose to all requests. Only use this on trusted networks.

The play view has NO permission gate — anyone reachable by the port can play. This matches the sharing model: kids WANT friends to play their carts, don't want strangers to edit them.

## 15.13 A worked example

Start a server:

```scheme
(define s (http/serve :port 8080 :cart-dir \"carts\" :compose-perm 'local-only))
(http/wait-until-ready s 2000)
```

Visit `http://localhost:8080/` in a browser. See the landing page. Click a cart link. See the play view.

Try to visit `/compose/synth-patch` from another machine on the network. Get a 403 (`compose is local-only`).

Stop:

```scheme
(http/stop s)
```

## 15.14 The cart directory

`:cart-dir \"carts\"` is a relative path. The server resolves it against the process's current working directory and refuses to escape the cwd.

If the resolved cart-dir does not exist, `http/serve` throws. If it exists but is not a directory, `http/serve` throws.

The server walks the cart-dir at request time (not startup) and lists `.slat` and `.sks` files. This means adding a new cart to the directory shows up on the next request without a server restart.

## 15.15 Cart naming rules

Cart names in URLs are limited to `[A-Za-z0-9._-]`. This excludes spaces, slashes (except as path separators within a subdirectory cart name), and any character that could carry a URL-encoding trick.

Kids naming carts should stick to lowercase letters, digits, hyphens, and underscores. `hero-sample`, `snake_v2`, `demo.1` all work. `hero sample` (with a space) does not — rename to `hero-sample`.

## 15.16 The security model in one paragraph

The HTTP server is a local sharing tool. Play is public within reach of the port. Compose is local-only by default. Path traversal is defended in depth. Only GET is accepted. Forwarded-for headers are ignored. Cart names are strict-regexed. The security review in the source (`lib/net/http-serve.js`) calls out each defense and its reasoning. Appendix H walks the whole model.

## 15.17 What to remember from this chapter

- `http/serve` starts a small HTTP server on a port, from a cart directory.
- `http/wait-until-ready` returns once the server has bound.
- `http/stop` closes the server.
- `http/serve-info` returns metadata about a running server.
- Three routes: `/` (landing), `/play/:cart` (public), `/compose/:cart` (permission-gated).
- `:compose-perm 'local-only` (default) restricts compose to 127.0.0.1 / ::1.
- Path traversal is defended: only alphanumeric-dot-underscore-hyphen cart names, no `..`, no null bytes, no header spoofing.
- Only GET is accepted. Writes come later.

Chapter 16 walks a full worked example — sprite plus sound plus tile-map plus HTTP publish plus friend plays.
")
